  <oversight_info>
    <has_dmc>No</has_dmc>
  </oversight_info>
  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Recently, a clinical trial showed that the use of lumbar drains compared to ventricular drain
      in patients suffering from subarachnoid hemorrhage resulted in less delayed ischemic
      neurological deficits but failed to show a clinical benefit after 6 months. The underlying
      assumption was, that the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) obtained from lumbar drains has a higher
      concentration of blood than CSF from lumbar drains. The investigators decided to test this
      assumption. In this study, the investigators will randomize patients to either placement of a
      ventricular or a lumbar drain and analyze the CSF drainage on a daily basis.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
